WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.300 --> 00:00:02.833
RONALD SMITH: Yeah, so
this is a long list of things

00:00:02.833 --> 00:00:06.733
that one might do to reduce
global warming.

00:00:06.733 --> 00:00:08.633
But they're all very difficult,
if not impossible.

00:00:11.633 --> 00:00:18.067
So are there any points that you
want to make about these?

00:00:18.067 --> 00:00:20.467
Any questions about what
I mean by them?

00:00:20.467 --> 00:00:21.967
I think we did go
over this last

00:00:21.967 --> 00:00:24.000
time, if I'm not mistaken.

00:00:26.567 --> 00:00:31.000
There are lots of other
recommendations or suggestions

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:33.767
that have been made under
the general title of

00:00:33.767 --> 00:00:35.967
geoengineering.

00:00:35.967 --> 00:00:41.800
But one I indicated there is
to install an umbrella-like

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:47.567
object out in space, somewhere
between the earth and the sun,

00:00:47.567 --> 00:00:51.700
so that it casts a shadow
on the earth.

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:54.667
And, therefore, reduces the
total amount of sunlight

00:00:54.667 --> 00:00:57.233
hitting the earth.

00:00:57.233 --> 00:01:01.067
A related suggestion is that
we put a layer of small

00:01:01.067 --> 00:01:06.167
particles, kind of like
volcanoes have done naturally

00:01:06.167 --> 00:01:09.767
from time to time, put a layer
of small particles in the

00:01:09.767 --> 00:01:13.433
stratosphere that will increase
the albedo of the

00:01:13.433 --> 00:01:17.900
earth and reflect the Sun's
radiation back into space, and

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:19.933
thereby cool the earth.

00:01:19.933 --> 00:01:23.533
The question for something like
that, though, is what

00:01:23.533 --> 00:01:25.500
material do we put in there?

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:28.067
They would have to be very fine
particles or they would

00:01:28.067 --> 00:01:31.000
just fall out.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.733
If they have some kind of weird
chemistry, like sulfate

00:01:33.733 --> 00:01:37.600
particles, what would they do
to the chemistry of the

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:38.167
atmosphere?

00:01:38.167 --> 00:01:41.967
So whenever you think of
something, some little clever

00:01:41.967 --> 00:01:45.700
idea pops into your mind,
unfortunately there's probably

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:51.167
100 unintended consequences on
these geoengineering ideas.

00:01:51.167 --> 00:01:54.000
So they have to be thought
through extremely carefully

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.700
before any of them could
be implemented.

00:02:03.567 --> 00:02:09.400
While climate research is quite
a mature area now, there

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:13.567
are some areas within it that
require further thought.

00:02:13.567 --> 00:02:17.500
For example, we're still missing
a complete theory of

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:18.667
the ice ages.

00:02:18.667 --> 00:02:22.133
We think that maybe this
Milankovitch forcing has

00:02:22.133 --> 00:02:22.767
played a role.

00:02:22.767 --> 00:02:27.900
But that Milankovitch forcing
is very weak actually.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:32.300
The obliquity change, the tilt
of the earth's axis, is only a

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:36.000
couple of degrees one
way or the other.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.700
The procession theory, which
changes the orientation of the

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:43.967
tilt of the earth's axis,
changes the way the seasons

00:02:43.967 --> 00:02:46.300
work, but oppositely in
the two hemispheres.

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:50.000
So if you're looking globally,
that influence cancels right

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:51.467
out completely.

00:02:51.467 --> 00:02:53.567
So you have to make up some
argument about why one

00:02:53.567 --> 00:02:55.933
hemisphere is more important
than the other.

00:02:55.933 --> 00:02:58.133
So we're missing a complete
theory there.

00:02:58.133 --> 00:03:02.533
We're also missing a theory
of Venus' climate history.

00:03:02.533 --> 00:03:06.033
How it got from being an
earth-like planet to something

00:03:06.033 --> 00:03:07.800
that's much, much hotter.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:10.733
And that's important, as I
mentioned, because there's

00:03:10.733 --> 00:03:14.800
some worry that the earth's
atmosphere might follow a

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:16.167
similar path.

00:03:16.167 --> 00:03:20.500
Theory of solar variability, now
we know that the sun has

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:25.033
gotten hotter over the
millennia, over

00:03:25.033 --> 00:03:28.233
the age of the earth.

00:03:28.233 --> 00:03:32.133
And we know that there's a
sunspot cycle, an 11 year and

00:03:32.133 --> 00:03:36.000
a 22 year cycle, on the number
of sun spots on the

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.100
surface of the Sun.

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:40.333
And we think that that may
have had a very minor

00:03:40.333 --> 00:03:44.167
influence on the amount of
radiation reaching the earth.

00:03:44.167 --> 00:03:47.300
But that theory is not
well fleshed out.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:49.600
There are some statistical
relationships

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:51.900
that have been proposed.

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:55.800
But the physical mechanisms for
this make almost no sense.

00:03:55.800 --> 00:04:00.567
And so we need to further
understand why the sun might

00:04:00.567 --> 00:04:03.433
vary in its strength and
what influence that

00:04:03.433 --> 00:04:05.767
would have on the earth.

00:04:05.767 --> 00:04:07.733
The theory of positive feedback
I'm going to be

00:04:07.733 --> 00:04:09.867
talking more about that
in just a minute--

00:04:09.867 --> 00:04:13.700
the idea that there are these
processes on earth that will

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:16.033
tend to amplify climate
change.

00:04:16.033 --> 00:04:18.700
The ones that we've talked about
already have been ice

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:21.033
albedo feedback.

00:04:21.033 --> 00:04:21.167
Right?

00:04:21.167 --> 00:04:25.067
More snow in a colder climate
makes the albedo larger,

00:04:25.067 --> 00:04:29.500
reflects more radiation, cools
the earth more, and that might

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.667
spiral on itself.

00:04:31.667 --> 00:04:34.267
There's the water
vapor feedback.

00:04:34.267 --> 00:04:37.967
A warmer climate would put
more water vapor in the

00:04:37.967 --> 00:04:39.667
atmosphere certainly.

00:04:39.667 --> 00:04:42.600
Water vapor is an important
greenhouse gas that would warm

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:44.900
the climate further and so on.

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:47.700
And then one that's been talked
about more recently,

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:51.100
seems to be going on with the
last 100 years or so, is

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:59.233
carbon dioxide feedback, where
a warmer climate is beginning

00:04:59.233 --> 00:05:05.700
to allow carbon trapped in
permafrost to decay and be

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:07.033
added to the atmosphere.

00:05:07.033 --> 00:05:12.000
Also ocean water, when you
heat it, it can hold less

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.867
carbon dioxide dissolved
in water.

00:05:15.867 --> 00:05:17.667
So that CO2 is going
to be added.

00:05:17.667 --> 00:05:20.833
So this acts on a slower time
scale perhaps, but there's

00:05:20.833 --> 00:05:24.533
some worry that there's a carbon
dioxide feedback that

00:05:24.533 --> 00:05:26.833
may be starting to happen.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:32.700
That one has to do--that last
one has to do with this next

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.767
one, how greenhouse
concentrations are controlled.

00:05:35.767 --> 00:05:37.967
We don't have a complete
understanding

00:05:37.967 --> 00:05:38.967
of the carbon cycle.

00:05:38.967 --> 00:05:43.567
Or how some of the other
greenhouse gases, like

00:05:43.567 --> 00:05:50.300
methane, ozone, oxides of
nitrogen there's not a

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:53.467
complete understanding of how
they are controlled in the

00:05:53.467 --> 00:05:54.733
earth's atmosphere.

00:05:54.733 --> 00:05:58.467
The last IPPC report, the one
that you've been looking at,

00:05:58.467 --> 00:06:05.900
the AR4, is full of apologies
for how little they can say

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.033
about regional climates.

00:06:09.033 --> 00:06:13.967
The problem is that these global
climate models roughly

00:06:13.967 --> 00:06:17.933
agree in their predictions of
how the global temperature

00:06:17.933 --> 00:06:18.400
will change.

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:22.367
But they disagree, to a large
extent, about how the climates

00:06:22.367 --> 00:06:25.167
of different continents and
different sub regions within

00:06:25.167 --> 00:06:27.167
continents will change.

00:06:27.167 --> 00:06:29.100
So this is a big area
of research.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:32.800
In fact, my group is interested
a little bit in how

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:38.667
global changes will influence
local and regional climates.

00:06:38.667 --> 00:06:41.833
We don't understand very well
how clouds would change,

00:06:41.833 --> 00:06:45.300
aerosols, how those two things
would impact the earth's

00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:47.133
albedo in a different climate.

00:06:47.133 --> 00:06:50.867
And this question of whether we
can re-bury carbon dioxide

00:06:50.867 --> 00:06:54.000
into the earth is receiving a
lot of funding and a lot of

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.233
research at the moment.

00:06:56.233 --> 00:06:58.033
Those are some of the
active areas.

00:06:58.033 --> 00:07:02.933
If any of you were to get
involved in climate research,

00:07:02.933 --> 00:07:05.700
there's a good chance you'd
probably be working on one of

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:08.667
those problems. Although, maybe
I've left off a couple

00:07:08.667 --> 00:07:10.767
of newly emerging ideas.

00:07:13.767 --> 00:07:17.000
So the last thing I want to
talk about in this set of

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
lectures is something called
climate sensitivity.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:28.467
And it's basically an attempt
to simplify and quantify how

00:07:28.467 --> 00:07:32.167
earth will respond, how the
earth's climate will respond,

00:07:32.167 --> 00:07:35.367
to changes in radiative
forcing.

00:07:38.067 --> 00:07:42.267
I'll define radiative forcing
in just a minute.

00:07:42.267 --> 00:07:48.800
There are two different common
definitions for climate

00:07:48.800 --> 00:07:49.600
sensitivity.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:51.400
So I need you to be aware
of both of these.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:55.633
So when you pick up a paper on
climate sensitivity you can

00:07:55.633 --> 00:07:59.533
spot which definition
the author is using.

00:07:59.533 --> 00:08:04.300
One definition is, how much
would the earth's climate warm

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:07.800
if there was a doubling
of CO2?

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:10.567
That's a commonly used
definition for climate

00:08:10.567 --> 00:08:11.867
sensitivity.

00:08:11.867 --> 00:08:15.000
The other one is, how much would
the earth warm if you

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.033
increased the radiation hitting
the surface of the

00:08:19.033 --> 00:08:24.333
earth by one watt per
square meter?

00:08:24.333 --> 00:08:28.633
Now these two things can be
related, roughly, because a

00:08:28.633 --> 00:08:33.233
CO2 doubling when you add CO2 to
the atmosphere you increase

00:08:33.233 --> 00:08:35.100
the absorption and the

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:38.533
re-emission of longwave
radiation.

00:08:38.533 --> 00:08:45.000
And a doubling of the CO2 is
approximately adding 3.7 watts

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.567
per square meter of radiative
forcing back to the

00:08:48.567 --> 00:08:50.100
surface of the earth.

00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:53.400
So you trap the outgoing
longwave radiation, you warm

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:56.233
the atmosphere, and then
that readmits back to

00:08:56.233 --> 00:08:58.933
earth about that much.

00:08:58.933 --> 00:09:02.300
So you can go back and forth
between those two definitions

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:07.800
using that kind of relationship,
that quantity.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:10.000
Now the reason I like it, the
reason I want to stick it in

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.600
here, is that it's being used
more and more as a compact way

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.333
to compare different models.

00:09:15.333 --> 00:09:18.200
For example, the National
Center for Atmospheric

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:20.600
Research has a global
climate model.

00:09:20.600 --> 00:09:23.367
The Department of Energy has
a global climate model.

00:09:23.367 --> 00:09:26.867
NASA has a global
climate model.

00:09:26.867 --> 00:09:32.033
Several in Europe, the
Russians have one.

00:09:32.033 --> 00:09:33.067
How do you compare them?

00:09:33.067 --> 00:09:39.233
One way is to use this measure
of their sensitivity.

00:09:39.233 --> 00:09:42.000
It's been found in that way
that there are some

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.267
significant differences
between these models.

00:09:44.267 --> 00:09:46.667
And it's been a help to
find out why these

00:09:46.667 --> 00:09:49.200
models are so different.

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:52.467
Also, it's a nice way to
summarize some paleoclimate

00:09:52.467 --> 00:09:56.700
data of the type that you and
I have been looking at a

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:57.833
couple of weeks ago.

00:09:57.833 --> 00:10:02.333
And I like it because it
illustrates the role of these

00:10:02.333 --> 00:10:03.233
climate feedbacks.

00:10:03.233 --> 00:10:06.300
So it turns out that these
climate sensitivity values,

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:11.333
almost no matter how you compute
them, are larger than

00:10:11.333 --> 00:10:16.200
you would expect if you left
off the feedbacks.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:19.500
And so by that increase in
sensitivity you can show what

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:22.633
role these climate feedbacks
are having.

00:10:22.633 --> 00:10:25.833
So for all these reasons,
we're going to

00:10:25.833 --> 00:10:26.700
take a look at this.

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:28.967
Now, so the definitions.

00:10:28.967 --> 00:10:31.500
Radiative forcing, extra
radiation at the earth's

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:35.100
surface relative to
preindustrial time.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:37.533
That's the way radiative forcing
is defined in the

00:10:37.533 --> 00:10:39.367
global warming debate.

00:10:39.367 --> 00:10:41.967
I wouldn't call that a
universal definition.

00:10:41.967 --> 00:10:43.100
But in the global
warming debate

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:44.600
that's how it's defined.

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:47.533
These are the primary feedbacks
we're talking about.

00:10:47.533 --> 00:10:51.733
And occasionally you'll find
a discussion of a runaway

00:10:51.733 --> 00:10:55.067
climate where the feedbacks, the
positive feedbacks, are so

00:10:55.067 --> 00:10:58.567
strong that they would take over
and drive the climate to

00:10:58.567 --> 00:11:02.467
an extreme state, like has
happened on Venus.

00:11:02.467 --> 00:11:05.600
Unlikely for earth, but it's
part of the conversation.

00:11:12.333 --> 00:11:17.833
I've got to define okay, now
there's another variable that

00:11:17.833 --> 00:11:22.467
comes in, in how you define
climate sensitivity.

00:11:22.467 --> 00:11:25.167
And that has to do with, what
feedbacks do you include in

00:11:25.167 --> 00:11:27.100
the calculation?

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:29.567
So I'm going to define something
called the Black

00:11:29.567 --> 00:11:34.233
Body sensitivity, which has
no feedbacks in it.

00:11:34.233 --> 00:11:36.733
It's based on the
Stefan-Boltzmann law only,

00:11:36.733 --> 00:11:40.200
which you remember, from earlier
in the course, is the

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:43.733
fact that the radiation emitted
from an object's

00:11:43.733 --> 00:11:48.833
surface goes like the fourth
power of the temperature.

00:11:48.833 --> 00:11:50.100
That was the Stefan-Boltzmann
law.

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:54.667
There's something called the
Charney sensitivity.

00:11:54.667 --> 00:11:59.600
Charney was a scientist
who chaired the first

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:02.967
investigative panel
on global warming.

00:12:02.967 --> 00:12:08.400
And he tried to base their final
report on a particular

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:12.933
definition of climate
sensitivity that included some

00:12:12.933 --> 00:12:16.967
short-term feedbacks,
but excluded some of

00:12:16.967 --> 00:12:18.067
the longer term ones.

00:12:18.067 --> 00:12:21.433
For example, he included water
vapor feedbacks, snow/albedo

00:12:21.433 --> 00:12:23.500
feedback, and cloud feedback.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:28.833
But he excluded any feedback
connected with the oceans, the

00:12:28.833 --> 00:12:31.867
ice sheets, or carbon
dioxide changes.

00:12:31.867 --> 00:12:35.200
And that's become known, in
the literature, as Charney

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:37.200
sensitivity.

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:45.667
It's probably valid on periods
of time of, say, well 20 to 50

00:12:45.667 --> 00:12:49.600
years, something like that.

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:53.067
When you go to longer terms,
however, maybe 100, 200, 300

00:12:53.067 --> 00:12:57.333
years, you have to realize that
other slower adjustments

00:12:57.333 --> 00:13:01.300
in the climate system are going
to be happening, such as

00:13:01.300 --> 00:13:05.133
changes to deep ocean
temperature, changes in the

00:13:05.133 --> 00:13:06.200
ice sheets.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:08.467
Sea level will be rising.

00:13:08.467 --> 00:13:11.267
Biomass on the continents
may be changing.

00:13:11.267 --> 00:13:17.867
And the carbon dioxide may be
responding to changes in the

00:13:17.867 --> 00:13:21.733
ocean and the land surface,
the land biomass.

00:13:21.733 --> 00:13:24.100
So that would be called
long-term sensitivity.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:32.700
Makes you realize this subject
is not dirt simple.

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:35.900
I mean, it's got some complexity
to it, depending on

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:39.300
the time frame that you're
talking about and the

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:42.467
feedbacks that you're allowing
in the calculation.

00:13:42.467 --> 00:13:45.267
So here's the easy one, Black
Body sensitivity.

00:13:48.033 --> 00:13:50.533
If I've got an object, like a
planet, receiving a certain

00:13:50.533 --> 00:13:54.400
amount of radiation from the
sun, you know that it'll

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:58.567
increase its temperature, or
adjust its temperature, so

00:13:58.567 --> 00:14:03.767
that it radiates to space
just as much as it's

00:14:03.767 --> 00:14:05.733
receiving from the sun.

00:14:05.733 --> 00:14:09.167
So it'll adjust it's own
temperature to come into that

00:14:09.167 --> 00:14:11.667
kind of radiative equilibrium.

00:14:11.667 --> 00:14:14.767
Well then, if I were to increase
the amount received

00:14:14.767 --> 00:14:20.067
from the sun by 1 watt per
square meter, how much must

00:14:20.067 --> 00:14:23.200
the temperature rise in order
to establish a new

00:14:23.200 --> 00:14:24.100
equilibrium?

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:26.667
Pretty simple idea, right?

00:14:26.667 --> 00:14:29.933
So there's the Stefan-Boltzmann
law.

00:14:29.933 --> 00:14:33.267
I'm going to do a quick little
calculus trick here that some

00:14:33.267 --> 00:14:34.733
of you may not be
familiar with.

00:14:34.733 --> 00:14:37.667
But if I take the derivative
of F with respect to

00:14:37.667 --> 00:14:41.067
temperature, I get 4 times sigma
T to the third times the

00:14:41.067 --> 00:14:43.233
change in temperature.

00:14:43.233 --> 00:14:48.767
And if I rearrange, bring the
dF under and that down under

00:14:48.767 --> 00:14:50.900
here, I get that formula.

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:57.267
The change in temperature for
each change in flux is given

00:14:57.267 --> 00:15:02.367
by 1 over 4 sigma
T to the third.

00:15:02.367 --> 00:15:03.467
I can plug numbers in.

00:15:03.467 --> 00:15:05.967
That Stefan-Boltzmann constant
is a fixed constant.

00:15:05.967 --> 00:15:10.633
I can use the temperature of
our planet, of 288 Kelvin,

00:15:10.633 --> 00:15:12.700
plug it into that formula.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:16.967
And I immediately get this
rather interesting number.

00:15:16.967 --> 00:15:21.500
For every watt per square meter
that I add to the earth

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:28.300
in the form of radiative energy,
it'll warm by 0.2

00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:31.100
degrees Kelvin.

00:15:31.100 --> 00:15:38.133
That is the simplest way to
compute climate sensitivity.

00:15:38.133 --> 00:15:41.300
That's a pretty small number.

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:44.567
And the reason why, as we will
see the reason why it's fairly

00:15:44.567 --> 00:15:46.400
small is we have not
included any of

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:47.667
these positive feedbacks.

00:15:51.467 --> 00:15:55.100
Now this is a calculation
you can do for yourself.

00:15:55.100 --> 00:16:00.833
Just try putting in different
values of F or T and computing

00:16:00.833 --> 00:16:05.267
it and you'll see that that is
the rate at which the two

00:16:05.267 --> 00:16:07.767
things are--the slope at which
the two things are related to

00:16:07.767 --> 00:16:09.333
each other.

00:16:09.333 --> 00:16:11.800
Any questions on that?

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:17.200
So we use this value as kind
of our foundation, right?

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:21.600
Now, if you look at the IPCC
report let me get the lights

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:29.400
down this summarizes the
radiative forcing, using the

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:31.167
definition that I gave
a moment ago.

00:16:31.167 --> 00:16:36.067
This is since the beginning of
the industrial revolution.

00:16:36.067 --> 00:16:39.867
It shows how much the radiation
reaching the surface

00:16:39.867 --> 00:16:44.367
of the earth has changed
and for what reason.

00:16:44.367 --> 00:16:48.000
Carbon dioxide is the
biggest reason.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.500
That increase in carbon dioxide,
we've seen, caused

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:59.333
about 1.7 watts per square meter
added greenhouse forcing

00:16:59.333 --> 00:17:00.767
at the surface of the earth.

00:17:00.767 --> 00:17:05.100
However, methane, N2O, and the
halocarbons have added

00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:07.200
something too.

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:11.133
Tropospheric ozone
has added more.

00:17:11.133 --> 00:17:13.867
And then on the negative side
and I talked about this a

00:17:13.867 --> 00:17:19.200
couple days ago aerosols, mostly
sulfate aerosols from

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:23.533
coal burning, has had
a negative effect.

00:17:23.533 --> 00:17:27.667
Well when you add all these
together, these

00:17:27.667 --> 00:17:28.933
roughly cancel these.

00:17:28.933 --> 00:17:31.667
And you get a value that's
about what CO2 would

00:17:31.667 --> 00:17:33.167
have been by itself.

00:17:33.167 --> 00:17:37.567
That doesn't mean that CO2
is alone in importance.

00:17:37.567 --> 00:17:38.567
The others are important too.

00:17:38.567 --> 00:17:41.700
But generally these cancel those
and you get a value of

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:47.733
about 1 and 1/2 meters
per second for

00:17:47.733 --> 00:17:49.167
the radiative forcing.

00:17:49.167 --> 00:17:53.900
And so if you then just use the
Black Body sensitivity for

00:17:53.900 --> 00:18:00.267
that, that would give
you about 0.3

00:18:00.267 --> 00:18:03.833
degree Kelvin warming.

00:18:03.833 --> 00:18:07.300
And we know, in fact, from our
data, that the warming of our

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:11.100
planet since the industrial
revolution began is about 0.8.

00:18:13.833 --> 00:18:16.733
So it's quite a bit larger
than this value.

00:18:16.733 --> 00:18:19.600
We can formalize that.

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:23.967
So let's try to compute
radiative forcing based on the

00:18:23.967 --> 00:18:26.600
data that we have.

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:31.533
Over the last 100 years we've
had about 0.8 degree warming.

00:18:31.533 --> 00:18:35.500
From the last slide, we've got
about 1.5 watts per square

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:38.000
meter radiative forcing.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:42.667
So if I divide one by the other,
I get a sensitivity

00:18:42.667 --> 00:18:47.067
based on the radiation
definition of 0.5 Kelvin.

00:18:47.067 --> 00:18:56.567
That then is about 2 and 1/2
times the sensitivity there.

00:18:56.567 --> 00:19:02.667
So the sensitivity that we're
seeing in our planet is about

00:19:02.667 --> 00:19:05.167
2 and 1/2 times what we compute
from a simple Black

00:19:05.167 --> 00:19:06.567
Body forcing law.

00:19:06.567 --> 00:19:10.133
This then, is evidence that the
feedbacks are working, the

00:19:10.133 --> 00:19:13.700
positive feedbacks
are working.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:18.200
You could re-formula that as
a warming per CO2 doubling.

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:22.533
And you get about 2 degrees
Kelvin for every CO2 doubling.

00:19:22.533 --> 00:19:24.800
I want to do this
one other way.

00:19:24.800 --> 00:19:28.300
I know I'm beating this to
death, but you remember this

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:33.900
plot, from the Pleistocene, the
advance and retreat of the

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:37.667
glaciers over the last
400,000 years.

00:19:37.667 --> 00:19:39.800
Well, here we have a temperature
signature on the

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:44.567
bottom and a CO2 signature
on the top.

00:19:44.567 --> 00:19:48.100
We can convert the
CO2 signature

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:51.367
to a radiative forcing.

00:19:51.367 --> 00:19:52.867
And here's how that
argument goes.

00:19:52.867 --> 00:19:57.933
So that's a warming of about 5
degrees between glacial and

00:19:57.933 --> 00:20:00.933
interglacial times.

00:20:00.933 --> 00:20:05.067
We estimate a change in the
longwave forcing of about 7

00:20:05.067 --> 00:20:07.433
watts per square meter.

00:20:07.433 --> 00:20:14.833
Divide one by the other, I get
about 0.7 degrees Kelvin per

00:20:14.833 --> 00:20:16.467
watt per square meter.

00:20:16.467 --> 00:20:18.967
Now that's slightly larger than
the one we had on the

00:20:18.967 --> 00:20:21.967
last slide from the
last 100 years.

00:20:21.967 --> 00:20:26.900
And most people believe that
that number is larger than the

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:33.733
what did we have for that 0.5,
0.7, because you get these

00:20:33.733 --> 00:20:38.133
extra long-term feedbacks
coming in.

00:20:38.133 --> 00:20:41.133
So there's still a lot of
argument in the literature

00:20:41.133 --> 00:20:41.733
about that.

00:20:41.733 --> 00:20:44.800
But the general interpretation
is that when you go to this

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:48.467
longer time scale of a couple
hundred thousand years, you

00:20:48.467 --> 00:20:51.633
get some longer--some other
positive feedbacks that make

00:20:51.633 --> 00:20:54.467
the climate even more sensitive

00:20:54.467 --> 00:20:57.767
to radiative forcing.

00:20:57.767 --> 00:20:59.000
Any questions on that?

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:09.067
Yeah, so I'll just wrap that up
by saying, as expected, our

00:21:09.067 --> 00:21:12.567
climate is about 3 times more
sensitive to radiative forcing

00:21:12.567 --> 00:21:17.200
than Black Body would suggest,
due to positive feedbacks like

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:19.867
water vapor feedback and
snow/albedo feedback.

00:21:19.867 --> 00:21:22.500
And when you go to longer time
scales, it becomes even

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:25.933
slightly more sensitive due to,

00:21:25.933 --> 00:21:28.533
possibly, some other feedbacks.

00:21:28.533 --> 00:21:29.400
Yes?

