00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:08.833
Yeah, okay.

00:22:08.833 --> 00:22:11.000
So that's the summary.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.500
So this is everything then.

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.100
We did all of these subjects.

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:18.667
And today we just finished
up the concept of climate

00:22:18.667 --> 00:22:20.400
sensitivity.

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:21.767
Are there any general questions

00:22:21.767 --> 00:22:23.067
about global warming?

00:22:28.567 --> 00:22:31.533
Okay, if not, we'll
leave it there.

00:22:31.533 --> 00:22:35.567
And I want to do one
other thing today.

00:22:35.567 --> 00:22:37.433
I think we can get it in.

00:22:51.333 --> 00:22:55.867
Yeah, because population is a
driver in global warming, I

00:22:55.867 --> 00:22:59.700
wanted to just to spend the rest
of the period I'm not an

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:04.367
expert in demography or
population studies.

00:23:04.367 --> 00:23:07.267
But there's a few things that
are quite obvious, that even I

00:23:07.267 --> 00:23:07.767
can understand.

00:23:07.767 --> 00:23:09.667
And I wanted to lay
those out for you.

00:23:12.267 --> 00:23:14.400
Because it's intimately
connected with all these

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:17.133
environmental issues, including
the air pollution

00:23:17.133 --> 00:23:21.367
which we'll be studying next
time and on Friday.

00:23:21.367 --> 00:23:24.833
So these are the terms you're
going to have to know.

00:23:24.833 --> 00:23:29.100
The fertility rate is the number
of children that a

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:32.067
woman would bear in
her lifetime.

00:23:32.067 --> 00:23:35.200
The growth rate of a population
would be the rate

00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:41.800
of change of the population as
a fraction of the existing

00:23:41.800 --> 00:23:42.467
population.

00:23:42.467 --> 00:23:45.500
In other words, a
relative rate.

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:49.633
Not a number of people per year,
but like a percent per

00:23:49.633 --> 00:23:51.967
year, or something like that.

00:23:51.967 --> 00:23:55.100
We'll talk about the special
case of exponential growth,

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:58.167
where the population would
follow a pure exponential

00:23:58.167 --> 00:24:02.667
curving rising curve.

00:24:02.667 --> 00:24:05.800
I'll talk about population
density, urbanization, the

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:07.600
so-called demographic
transition, and

00:24:07.600 --> 00:24:08.800
the population pyramid.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:11.767
So in the next few minutes, I'll
introduce each of these

00:24:11.767 --> 00:24:14.267
terms.

00:24:14.267 --> 00:24:18.567
Population versus time, going
back 50,000 years, human

00:24:18.567 --> 00:24:24.267
population rose very slowly
over most of the period of

00:24:24.267 --> 00:24:31.067
time when humans were evolving,
because, well, life

00:24:31.067 --> 00:24:33.700
is difficult.

00:24:33.700 --> 00:24:38.367
The death rate was high due to
disease, due to accidents, due

00:24:38.367 --> 00:24:40.033
to all kinds of things.

00:24:40.033 --> 00:24:43.433
And it isn't really until you
got in the very recent period

00:24:43.433 --> 00:24:46.833
of time where you began to get
this rapid, very rapid,

00:24:46.833 --> 00:24:48.833
increase in human population.

00:24:48.833 --> 00:24:55.033
Probably the biggest change in
the rate of growth had to do

00:24:55.033 --> 00:25:01.567
with the changes in medicine, I
would say the germ theory of

00:25:01.567 --> 00:25:05.567
disease and inoculations.

00:25:05.567 --> 00:25:07.200
Both of which are
rather recent.

00:25:07.200 --> 00:25:10.633
We're talking about the 19th,
in some cases the early part

00:25:10.633 --> 00:25:12.067
of the 20th century.

00:25:12.067 --> 00:25:19.000
1920, 1930, 1940 when mass
inoculations began to be used.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:23.500
Anyway it's a very curious
curve, so slow and so flat for

00:25:23.500 --> 00:25:29.033
so long, and then rising so
rapidly now just in the last

00:25:29.033 --> 00:25:32.400
100 years or so.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:36.467
That is partly controlled
by the fertility rate.

00:25:36.467 --> 00:25:42.000
And here's a diagram from
Wiki about that.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.933
What you have for each country
and this is by country is a

00:25:45.933 --> 00:25:49.867
fertility rate from
0--or from 1 to 7.

00:25:49.867 --> 00:25:52.333
So the United States
would have a value

00:25:52.333 --> 00:25:54.533
somewhere around 2.

00:25:54.533 --> 00:26:01.000
Remember this is the number of
births per woman in her life.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:06.067
And a lot of other countries
have that medium gray color,

00:26:06.067 --> 00:26:09.333
which puts you around 2.

00:26:09.333 --> 00:26:13.633
The Soviet Union, especially
Ukraine, is even less than

00:26:13.633 --> 00:26:15.967
that, however.

00:26:15.967 --> 00:26:19.733
And most of Africa and the
Middle East are dramatically

00:26:19.733 --> 00:26:24.167
higher, generally in
the range 4, 5, 6.

00:26:24.167 --> 00:26:26.567
That doesn't necessarily mean
that their population is

00:26:26.567 --> 00:26:30.067
increasing rapidly, although
that's true also.

00:26:30.067 --> 00:26:33.467
But the fertility rate is one of
the components that goes in

00:26:33.467 --> 00:26:39.267
to determining the rate
of population growth.

00:26:39.267 --> 00:26:44.600
Everybody understand this
definition of fertility rate?

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:47.967
It's controlled by a number
of factors, but a

00:26:47.967 --> 00:26:51.100
lot of it is cultural.

00:26:51.100 --> 00:26:56.567
A lot of it has to do with
expectations, having children

00:26:56.567 --> 00:26:58.700
to take care of you in your
old age, to help with the

00:26:58.700 --> 00:27:04.933
farm, or because you don't
have a way to control

00:27:04.933 --> 00:27:07.100
population.

00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:08.567
A number of--a wide variety
of things come into

00:27:08.567 --> 00:27:09.867
the fertility rate.

00:27:09.867 --> 00:27:14.400
The role of women in society
is a big one as well.

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:19.533
Here's the fertility rate
plotted versus GDP, the Gross

00:27:19.533 --> 00:27:23.300
Domestic Product, that makes
it pretty clear there's a

00:27:23.300 --> 00:27:27.133
relationship between how much
money people have, their

00:27:27.133 --> 00:27:29.967
standard of living, and
the fertility rate.

00:27:29.967 --> 00:27:32.367
USA is here.

00:27:32.367 --> 00:27:36.300
Generally, for the developed
world the fertility

00:27:36.300 --> 00:27:40.300
rate is 2 or less.

00:27:40.300 --> 00:27:44.500
Whereas for the underdeveloped
world the fertility rate can

00:27:44.500 --> 00:27:45.567
be very much higher.

00:27:45.567 --> 00:27:51.533
And this magic value here, of
2.3, is the replacement rate.

00:27:51.533 --> 00:27:55.233
You have to have a fertility
rate of about 2.3 in order to

00:27:55.233 --> 00:27:56.633
maintain a steady population.

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:04.767
There are a few outliers that
have to do with the special

00:28:04.767 --> 00:28:08.133
cultural conditions of
those countries.

00:28:12.467 --> 00:28:16.067
Stop me if there are
questions on this.

00:28:16.067 --> 00:28:19.867
So let's look at the fertility
rate for the United States and

00:28:19.867 --> 00:28:23.700
Canada since 1940.

00:28:23.700 --> 00:28:27.933
There was a big bulge in
fertility rate, reaching 3.7

00:28:27.933 --> 00:28:31.333
for the USA around 1955.

00:28:31.333 --> 00:28:34.067
And that is really what's
responsible for what's called

00:28:34.067 --> 00:28:36.467
the Baby Boom in the
United States.

00:28:36.467 --> 00:28:39.733
And I guess you are the children
of the Baby Boom

00:28:39.733 --> 00:28:43.967
generation or something
approximate to that.

00:28:43.967 --> 00:28:48.100
And then immediately after that
came a movement called

00:28:48.100 --> 00:28:52.467
ZPG, Zero Population Growth.

00:28:52.467 --> 00:28:55.067
Maybe that movement caused this
drop, or maybe it was

00:28:55.067 --> 00:28:58.400
just changes in background
cultural or economic

00:28:58.400 --> 00:28:58.800
conditions.

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:02.233
But there was a dramatic drop
in the fertility rate in the

00:29:02.233 --> 00:29:09.967
United States from 3.7
down to less than 2.

00:29:09.967 --> 00:29:12.867
And now it's come up a little
bit for the United States to

00:29:12.867 --> 00:29:16.567
just about the replacement
rate.

00:29:16.567 --> 00:29:18.200
Canada is roughly similar.

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:20.767
The details may be a little
different, they haven't jumped

00:29:20.767 --> 00:29:21.433
up at the end.

00:29:21.433 --> 00:29:25.300
But they followed roughly
the same curve.

00:29:25.300 --> 00:29:26.533
Any questions on that?

00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:30.800
So this is a wild
swing, right?

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:34.367
This is a huge variation in
just a few years in one

00:29:34.367 --> 00:29:37.467
particular country.

00:29:37.467 --> 00:29:41.433
Europe is famous for having
a low fertility rate.

00:29:41.433 --> 00:29:43.067
And here are some
of the numbers.

00:29:43.067 --> 00:29:44.767
Remember the replacement
rate is about 2.3.

00:29:48.133 --> 00:29:50.667
Italy has 1.3.

00:29:50.667 --> 00:29:54.300
And some of the Eastern European
countries are even

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:56.200
lower than that.

00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:57.200
France is higher.

00:29:57.200 --> 00:30:00.200
They've tried to keep their
population, their

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:01.400
fertility rate up.

00:30:01.400 --> 00:30:05.133
But they don't have it quite
at replacement levels.

00:30:05.133 --> 00:30:07.267
And Spain is down
at 1.3 as well.

00:30:07.267 --> 00:30:11.233
So Europe, as a whole, generally
has a very low

00:30:11.233 --> 00:30:13.400
fertility rate.

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:21.000
We saw that in the earlier map
as well, here, as opposed to

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.633
some other developing
parts of the world.

00:30:26.367 --> 00:30:29.300
And China has gone through
wild swings, as

00:30:29.300 --> 00:30:31.267
has the United States.

00:30:31.267 --> 00:30:33.800
For somewhat different reasons,
perhaps, but the

00:30:33.800 --> 00:30:38.567
curve is somewhat similar.

00:30:38.567 --> 00:30:41.967
It climbed even higher than the
United States, much higher

00:30:41.967 --> 00:30:44.500
in fact, up to 6.5.

00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:49.167
And that, I think, was part of
the cultural revolution where

00:30:49.167 --> 00:30:53.433
it was every woman's duty to
have as many children as she

00:30:53.433 --> 00:30:57.433
possibly could for the strength
of the state.

00:30:57.433 --> 00:31:02.067
And then talk about a complete
turnabout they've now dropped

00:31:02.067 --> 00:31:03.900
down to less than 2.

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:07.600
And, of course, that is largely
due to China's one

00:31:07.600 --> 00:31:12.467
child policy, kind of flipping
the political pressure on

00:31:12.467 --> 00:31:14.433
families and individuals.

00:31:14.433 --> 00:31:17.400
So wild swings in
fertility rate.

00:31:20.167 --> 00:31:22.700
Now we'll move to this
fractional growth rate then.

00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:31.100
So, of course, this is now a
combination of birth rate and

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:32.633
mortality rate.

00:31:32.633 --> 00:31:34.033
How many children are
born every year?

00:31:34.033 --> 00:31:35.633
How many people die
every year?

00:31:35.633 --> 00:31:38.867
You have to know both of those
to then get the total

00:31:38.867 --> 00:31:42.433
fractional growth rate
of the population.

00:31:42.433 --> 00:31:49.000
And there again, these colors
follow the same trend.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:54.300
As the Soviet Union has the
lowest growth rate, well 1--

00:31:54.300 --> 00:31:55.767
well below 0.

00:31:55.767 --> 00:31:57.533
They're losing population.

00:31:57.533 --> 00:32:03.567
And all the other countries are
gaining population, but at

00:32:03.567 --> 00:32:10.300
a rate ranging from 3% per year
to just a small fraction

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:14.033
of a percent per year.

00:32:14.033 --> 00:32:17.367
So that's the total fractional
growth rate.

00:32:17.367 --> 00:32:19.300
Here is the way you would
compute that.

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:20.133
Here are some numbers.

00:32:20.133 --> 00:32:26.000
For example, China population
in 2010 and 1990.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.733
Well that's a 20 year span, so
you can get an approximation

00:32:29.733 --> 00:32:34.700
by just taking the percent
change over that period of

00:32:34.700 --> 00:32:38.033
time and dividing that by
the number of years.

00:32:38.033 --> 00:32:41.633
So divide that by 20 and you
get a value that's just

00:32:41.633 --> 00:32:45.000
slightly less than
1% per year.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.200
And that would be that percent,
or that fractional

00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:51.700
growth rate for population
in China.

00:32:51.700 --> 00:32:53.167
That's how you do
the calculation.

00:32:53.167 --> 00:32:57.633
In some cases taking a 20 year
estimate might be blurring

00:32:57.633 --> 00:32:59.200
some details.

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:02.367
If the growth has been changing
rapidly over time,

00:33:02.367 --> 00:33:06.233
what you would be getting here
is some kind of average over a

00:33:06.233 --> 00:33:09.233
fluctuating quantity.

00:33:09.233 --> 00:33:12.433
But nevertheless, you see how
easy it is to do that

00:33:12.433 --> 00:33:17.133
calculation, if you don't mind
losing some of the details,

00:33:17.133 --> 00:33:18.933
some of the rapid
changes in time.

00:33:23.567 --> 00:33:30.033
So globally then, this is what
the fractional growth rate has

00:33:30.033 --> 00:33:33.433
been doing and is
projected to do.

00:33:33.433 --> 00:33:35.233
But these projections
are quite uncertain.

00:33:35.233 --> 00:33:37.933
I wouldn't pay too much
attention to the blue curve.

00:33:40.567 --> 00:33:44.067
Globally we've had, over the
last couple of decades, we've

00:33:44.067 --> 00:33:46.533
had growth rates--

00:33:46.533 --> 00:33:49.200
this is not fertility rate,
this is growth rate--

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:56.133
of about 2% per year, which is
quite a large growth rate.

00:33:56.133 --> 00:33:57.400
It has been decreasing.

00:33:57.400 --> 00:34:02.067
At the present time, it's
more like 1% per year.

00:34:02.067 --> 00:34:06.300
But that's still quite
a large growth rate.

00:34:06.300 --> 00:34:08.167
And then it's predicted
that will continue to

00:34:08.167 --> 00:34:10.267
drop as we go forward.

00:34:10.267 --> 00:34:14.667
But that will depend a lot upon
the future economy, the

00:34:14.667 --> 00:34:18.967
future cultural development of
the countries that have the

00:34:18.967 --> 00:34:20.233
highest populations.

00:34:23.733 --> 00:34:27.433
Now this concept of exponential
growth, you've

00:34:27.433 --> 00:34:30.867
probably heard it.

00:34:30.867 --> 00:34:34.267
If the fractional growth rate is
constant, that is, if this

00:34:34.267 --> 00:34:39.433
quantity were constant in time,
over some period of

00:34:39.433 --> 00:34:46.067
time, then the population
will grow exponentially.

00:34:46.067 --> 00:34:48.033
Now what does that mean, to
say the population grows

00:34:48.033 --> 00:34:48.800
exponentially?

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:53.300
The exponential function defines
a system whose annual

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:59.400
increase is proportional to
the population itself.

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.833
In other words, its rate of
increase is proportional to

00:35:03.833 --> 00:35:06.400
the population that it has.

00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:09.933
That is what is meant by an
exponential increase.

00:35:09.933 --> 00:35:12.467
Sometimes that word
is misused.

00:35:12.467 --> 00:35:14.567
Sometimes in the popular
literature someone will be

00:35:14.567 --> 00:35:20.033
saying, well, you know I'm rich,
my bank account amount

00:35:20.033 --> 00:35:21.433
is growing exponentially.

00:35:21.433 --> 00:35:25.167
And by that he might
just mean rapidly.

00:35:25.167 --> 00:35:27.200
But that's not what exponential
really means.

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:32.300
Exponential means it's growing
at a rate proportional to how

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:32.900
much you have.

00:35:32.900 --> 00:35:37.633
Now, if you're getting a fixed
interest rate in your account,

00:35:37.633 --> 00:35:40.633
then it would be exponential.

00:35:40.633 --> 00:35:43.367
It'll grow at a rate that will
increase as you get more and

00:35:43.367 --> 00:35:44.600
more money in the bank.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:46.533
So that might be an accurate
representation.

00:35:46.533 --> 00:35:52.000
Remember, exponential doesn't
refer to some rate of

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:55.967
increase, it relates to the
relationship between the rate

00:35:55.967 --> 00:35:59.267
of increase and the amount of
the standing population that

00:35:59.267 --> 00:36:02.233
you have at any particular
moment.

00:36:02.233 --> 00:36:05.433
So in other words, births
minus deaths, really,

00:36:05.433 --> 00:36:07.733
proportional to population.

00:36:07.733 --> 00:36:09.500
So we write it this way.

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:12.033
Population, as a function
of time, is given by the

00:36:12.033 --> 00:36:19.133
population at some reference
time, call it 0, and then P to

00:36:19.133 --> 00:36:25.100
the plus alpha t, where alpha
is the growth rate and t is

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:28.233
the time that's elapsed
since your

00:36:28.233 --> 00:36:31.867
reference time has occurred.

00:36:31.867 --> 00:36:37.433
So if the growth rate, for
example, is 1% per year--

00:36:37.433 --> 00:36:41.500
and that was a number
that we have about

00:36:41.500 --> 00:36:45.867
now for planet earth--

00:36:45.867 --> 00:36:48.333
and if that were to
remain constant.

00:36:48.333 --> 00:36:52.967
in other words, if this curve
was level at 1% per year, then

00:36:52.967 --> 00:36:56.433
here's how you could
do the calculation.

00:36:56.433 --> 00:37:03.933
After 100 years, putting in 100
years into there and 0.01

00:37:03.933 --> 00:37:09.667
year to the minus 1 in for
alpha, the units will cancel.

00:37:09.667 --> 00:37:16.467
And in this case, the product is
equal to 1, in this special

00:37:16.467 --> 00:37:17.633
simple example.

00:37:17.633 --> 00:37:21.833
So it's going to be exp to the
1, which has a value-- you can

00:37:21.833 --> 00:37:23.233
check it on your calculator--

00:37:23.233 --> 00:37:25.100
of 2.7.

00:37:25.100 --> 00:37:30.900
So a growth rate of 0.01 over
100 years would give a growth

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:32.533
rate factor of 2.7.

00:37:32.533 --> 00:37:35.633
So however many people you had
at the beginning of the 100

00:37:35.633 --> 00:37:40.167
year period, put that there,
multiply it times 2.7, and

00:37:40.167 --> 00:37:40.700
you'll get--

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:43.767
it's roughly a tripling, roughly
a tripling of the

00:37:43.767 --> 00:37:48.767
population over 100 years if you
have a growth rate of 1%

00:37:48.767 --> 00:37:50.767
percent per year.

00:37:50.767 --> 00:37:54.933
Remember it's compound interest.
The rate increases

00:37:54.933 --> 00:37:56.267
as the population increases.

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:01.300
Questions on that?

00:38:01.300 --> 00:38:04.067
Now this is a bit of a fiction,
because, as you've

00:38:04.067 --> 00:38:07.700
just seen, population
growth rates change

00:38:07.700 --> 00:38:10.400
quite a bit over time.

00:38:10.400 --> 00:38:16.467
And so, while you can do rough
calculations with this, a real

00:38:16.467 --> 00:38:19.600
population demographer would
probably never use this.

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:22.433
He would go step by step and
calculate it assuming a

00:38:22.433 --> 00:38:26.700
variable growth rate rather than
assuming a constant one.

00:38:29.700 --> 00:38:33.400
So here are the current
UN population

00:38:33.400 --> 00:38:37.167
projections for our planet.

00:38:37.167 --> 00:38:40.733
Data up to this point, and then
uncertain projections,

00:38:40.733 --> 00:38:43.200
depending on what you think
the growth rate will

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:44.767
be around the world.

00:38:47.667 --> 00:38:52.333
So we crossed 6 billion back
in 2000, roughly 2000.

00:38:52.333 --> 00:38:56.433
We crossed 7 billion just,
what was that, 3

00:38:56.433 --> 00:39:00.767
weeks ago, I think.

00:39:00.767 --> 00:39:05.233
And in the future, well
the projections vary

00:39:05.233 --> 00:39:06.867
all over the place.

00:39:06.867 --> 00:39:12.133
But by, let's say, 2080, this
looks like 2080, some

00:39:12.133 --> 00:39:15.667
calculations would have
us at 12 billion.

00:39:15.667 --> 00:39:17.467
Some would have us at 9.

00:39:17.467 --> 00:39:20.467
And some would have us
declining, population already

00:39:20.467 --> 00:39:24.867
getting back towards
6 billion.

00:39:24.867 --> 00:39:27.167
So great uncertainties
in this.

00:39:27.167 --> 00:39:33.300
But still great potential for
environmental difficulties, if

00:39:33.300 --> 00:39:36.700
either of those curves
are realized.

00:39:41.867 --> 00:39:45.133
Another issue that comes up
is population density.

00:39:45.133 --> 00:39:50.367
How many people per square
kilometer do you have?

00:39:50.367 --> 00:39:53.967
And this is a map of
population density.

00:39:53.967 --> 00:39:56.900
Units are people per
square kilometer.

00:39:56.900 --> 00:39:58.833
And there are some countries--

00:39:58.833 --> 00:40:02.367
and this is by country so this
can be quite misleading,

00:40:02.367 --> 00:40:07.167
because for a given country they
put a uniform color over

00:40:07.167 --> 00:40:08.967
the whole country.

00:40:08.967 --> 00:40:13.733
So it's the total population
divided by the total area of

00:40:13.733 --> 00:40:17.433
the country, then painted
as a uniform color

00:40:17.433 --> 00:40:18.267
over the whole country.

00:40:18.267 --> 00:40:19.433
That's quite unrealistic.

00:40:19.433 --> 00:40:22.467
But it will give us a place
to start to talk

00:40:22.467 --> 00:40:24.100
about population density.

00:40:24.100 --> 00:40:27.900
India, as a country, has a
population exceeding 1,000

00:40:27.900 --> 00:40:32.667
people per square kilometer,
which is enormous.

00:40:32.667 --> 00:40:35.300
Whereas something like Australia
is in the lightest

00:40:35.300 --> 00:40:39.033
shade that they have,
less than 10

00:40:39.033 --> 00:40:41.700
people per square kilometer.

00:40:44.700 --> 00:40:47.100
Wide variation in
that quantity.

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:49.867
But again, this is quite
misleading because it's done

00:40:49.867 --> 00:40:51.933
by country.

00:40:51.933 --> 00:40:55.867
United States, this is
per square mile.

00:40:55.867 --> 00:40:59.167
Remember, the United States
unfortunately is still on an

00:40:59.167 --> 00:41:00.833
old English system of measure.

00:41:00.833 --> 00:41:06.233
So very often you'll find
population per square mile

00:41:06.233 --> 00:41:07.600
instead of per square
kilometer.

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:12.100
You can do the conversion easily
to go back and forth.

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:15.267
But once again, doing it by
state is misleading, because

00:41:15.267 --> 00:41:17.333
there are parts of California
that are

00:41:17.333 --> 00:41:18.767
nearly empty of people.

00:41:18.767 --> 00:41:21.367
And there are very densely
populated areas of

00:41:21.367 --> 00:41:23.533
California and so on.

00:41:23.533 --> 00:41:26.667
But even averaging over states,
you'll find a big

00:41:26.667 --> 00:41:31.100
difference between Montana, for
example, and New Jersey

00:41:31.100 --> 00:41:32.600
and Rhode Island.

00:41:35.633 --> 00:41:38.633
Now, if you want to read
about the role

00:41:38.633 --> 00:41:41.500
of population density--

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:45.733
not all demographers would put a
great emphasis on population

00:41:45.733 --> 00:41:49.833
density, but Jared Diamond,
in this book, Collapse--

00:41:49.833 --> 00:41:51.233
how many have read that book?

00:41:51.233 --> 00:41:54.667
I thought a few of you would
have. He, in places in that

00:41:54.667 --> 00:41:57.867
book, makes a pretty strong
case for the importance of

00:41:57.867 --> 00:41:59.333
population density.

00:41:59.333 --> 00:42:02.767
He really thinks it matters that
populations have enough

00:42:02.767 --> 00:42:04.767
space to live.

00:42:04.767 --> 00:42:06.167
And I partly agree with that.

00:42:06.167 --> 00:42:08.967
But he maybe takes it--

00:42:08.967 --> 00:42:12.667
some examples he gives wouldn't
carry over to other

00:42:12.667 --> 00:42:15.367
civilizations that he didn't
talk about in his book.

00:42:15.367 --> 00:42:17.700
But anyway, he makes a strong
case for the importance of

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:18.900
population density.

00:42:18.900 --> 00:42:20.267
And I party believe that too.

00:42:20.267 --> 00:42:23.067
So I encourage you to take a
look at that book if you get a

00:42:23.067 --> 00:42:27.067
chance, because it makes the
case very nicely for the

00:42:27.067 --> 00:42:28.600
importance of population
density.

00:42:31.333 --> 00:42:34.967
When you think about what the
limiting resources are for

00:42:34.967 --> 00:42:41.300
living on our planet, water,
food, energy, living space,

00:42:41.300 --> 00:42:44.600
even these other ones, like
water and food and energy, to

00:42:44.600 --> 00:42:50.667
some extent they all depend on
having enough area as well.

00:42:50.667 --> 00:42:56.100
For example, energy from
hydroelectric requires a large

00:42:56.100 --> 00:43:00.767
catchment area of rain in order
to get hydroelectric.

00:43:00.767 --> 00:43:04.967
Farmland, obviously food from
farms requires lots of area.

00:43:04.967 --> 00:43:08.733
So just scanning this list and
realizing that many of those

00:43:08.733 --> 00:43:16.333
have a relationship to
population density would, I

00:43:16.333 --> 00:43:22.500
think, partly confirm Jared
Diamond's idea that living

00:43:22.500 --> 00:43:26.200
space is an important part of
the success of a culture.

00:43:29.567 --> 00:43:34.033
Okay, now to correct the
misimpression from those

00:43:34.033 --> 00:43:37.767
earlier country-based and

00:43:37.767 --> 00:43:40.333
state-based population
densities.

00:43:40.333 --> 00:43:44.133
People don't live uniformly
distributed over a

00:43:44.133 --> 00:43:46.333
country or a state.

00:43:46.333 --> 00:43:50.900
In fact, a higher and higher
fraction of populations are

00:43:50.900 --> 00:43:52.267
moving to cities.

00:43:52.267 --> 00:43:54.900
They're abandoning the land
and moving to cities.

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:59.833
So this is a plot, on the x-axis
1950 into the future,

00:43:59.833 --> 00:44:04.667
2050, the percent of the
population that's living in

00:44:04.667 --> 00:44:07.033
urban versus rural areas.

00:44:07.033 --> 00:44:12.300
Back in the 1950's, 70%
was rural, 30% urban.

00:44:12.300 --> 00:44:15.867
And we've crossed that boundary,
we've crossed that

00:44:15.867 --> 00:44:17.233
crossover point.

00:44:17.233 --> 00:44:19.900
And in the future, we'll have
more people living clustered

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:21.467
together in cities.

00:44:21.467 --> 00:44:23.433
That doesn't mean they don't
need the land around the

00:44:23.433 --> 00:44:26.433
cities to grow the food and
provide the energy and so on.

00:44:26.433 --> 00:44:30.267
But at least their living
density is much larger than

00:44:30.267 --> 00:44:34.200
those country-averaged or those
state-averaged values

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:36.067
that I gave you.

00:44:36.067 --> 00:44:39.467
And these are some of the
growing megacities, where now

00:44:39.467 --> 00:44:44.133
more than half the people in
the world are concentrated

00:44:44.133 --> 00:44:45.733
into these large cities.

00:44:45.733 --> 00:44:46.133
Yes?

00:44:46.133 --> 00:44:47.400
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:44:55.367 --> 00:44:56.833
PROFESSOR: I don't know.

00:44:56.833 --> 00:44:59.600
When you do calculations--

00:44:59.600 --> 00:45:03.767
I saw an article recently about
how much energy people

00:45:03.767 --> 00:45:07.667
used that live in New York city
versus the rest of New

00:45:07.667 --> 00:45:09.500
York state.

00:45:09.500 --> 00:45:12.467
And the people who live in New
York city use less energy per

00:45:12.467 --> 00:45:16.533
capita then the people that
live in upstate New York.

00:45:16.533 --> 00:45:19.233
Probably because of the dense
way that they live and the way

00:45:19.233 --> 00:45:23.100
that transportation is so much
easier when you live close.

00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:25.633
So I think it could be argued
that this might be a more

00:45:25.633 --> 00:45:27.367
efficient way to live.

00:45:27.367 --> 00:45:28.700
But that's only one measure.

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:32.767
And I haven't studied the issue
in it's full breadth.

00:45:32.767 --> 00:45:34.167
So that would be worth
looking into.

00:45:34.167 --> 00:45:37.033
To see whether this might
actually be an advantage for

00:45:37.033 --> 00:45:44.133
the environment, to have people
clustered in cities.

00:45:44.133 --> 00:45:46.367
Other comments on that?

00:45:46.367 --> 00:45:47.400
We need to wrap up.

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:48.633
I do need to give you this.

00:45:48.633 --> 00:45:51.000
So there's something called the
demographic transition.

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:57.300
And it goes basically from a
third world country converting

00:45:57.300 --> 00:45:58.833
to a first world country.

00:45:58.833 --> 00:46:01.433
What happens to its
population?

00:46:01.433 --> 00:46:04.933
In the beginning, you've got a
high birth rate, a high death

00:46:04.933 --> 00:46:06.600
rate, and a small population.

00:46:09.700 --> 00:46:14.633
Standard of living begins to
increase, health is improved.

00:46:14.633 --> 00:46:18.533
The first thing that happens
is the death rate drops.

00:46:18.533 --> 00:46:21.000
The birth rate stays high.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:22.767
Because the death rate has
dropped and the birth rate

00:46:22.767 --> 00:46:26.400
stays high, population
begins to increase.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:29.467
Then, at some point culturally,
the birth rate

00:46:29.467 --> 00:46:31.233
drops as well.

00:46:31.233 --> 00:46:34.033
You end up with a lower birth
rate and a lower death rate

00:46:34.033 --> 00:46:35.900
and a larger total population.

00:46:35.900 --> 00:46:38.700
We've seen this happen in
country after country.

00:46:38.700 --> 00:46:41.367
And if you look at that map
of the world, clearly some

00:46:41.367 --> 00:46:44.567
countries in the west,
like the US and

00:46:44.567 --> 00:46:46.367
Europe are in this state.

00:46:46.367 --> 00:46:47.967
And a lot of the third
world countries are

00:46:47.967 --> 00:46:48.967
still in this state.

00:46:48.967 --> 00:46:52.000
And a few are in the middle,
doing the demographic

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:53.567
transition.

00:46:53.567 --> 00:46:57.467
So this is an important concept
of how you go from one

00:46:57.467 --> 00:47:01.467
type of population situation
to the other.

00:47:01.467 --> 00:47:02.667
And the other one I want
to leave you with--

00:47:02.667 --> 00:47:04.467
I'm out of time-- but you
have to know about

00:47:04.467 --> 00:47:05.767
the population pyramid.

00:47:05.767 --> 00:47:12.067
So a country that has a stable
population, here's a plot of

00:47:12.067 --> 00:47:14.200
how many people you have,
male and female, in

00:47:14.200 --> 00:47:17.367
different age groups.

00:47:17.367 --> 00:47:20.133
A country that has a stable
population usually has a

